Close
DIZZINESS; PAIN AT INJECTION SITE; VACCINE ADMINISTERED IN PATIENT OF INAPPROPRIATE AGE; OFF LABEL USE; This spontaneous report received from a parent concerned a 17 year old female. The patient's height, and weight were not reported. The patient's pre-existing medical conditions included the patient had no known allergies and no medical history. The patient received covid-19 vaccine ad26.cov2.s (suspension for injection, route of admin not reported, batch number: 203A21A expiry: UNKNOWN) dose was not reported, administered on 10-APR-2021 for prophylactic vaccination. No concomitant medications were reported. On 10-APR-2021, the subject experienced dizziness. On 10-APR-2021, the subject experienced pain at injection site. On 10-APR-2021, the subject experienced vaccine administered in subject of inappropriate age. On 10-APR-2021, the subject experienced off label use. The action taken with covid-19 vaccine ad26.cov2.s was not applicable. The patient had not recovered from dizziness, and pain at injection site, and the outcome of vaccine administered in patient of inappropriate age and off label use was not reported. This report was non-serious.

Janssen COVID-19 Vaccine Chills, muscle aches, mild headache, a sudden reduced ability to hear and see, cold sweat, lightheadedness, disorientation Starting at approximately 1:00 am on 4/08/21 I woke up with a throbbing left arm, muscle aches, a very mild headache, and chills accompanied by bouts of uncontrollable shivering. I experienced these cold like symptoms throughout the night. At around 6:00 am, I woke up with a very mild headache and muscle aches. I took my temperature, and had a 101 degree Fahrenheit fever. I rested, and took my temperature multiple times that morning-- which had been gradually decreasing. At around 11:30/12:00 I experienced a sudden onset of extreme fatigue followed closely by a greatly reduced ability to hear and see, along with extreme lightheadedness and the feeling like I was going to pass out. I suddenly became cold, and my body was drenched in sweat in a matter of seconds. I think the whole experience lasted around 10 minutes, before it eventually began to pass. I could see clearly again and began to regain my hearing, however I still experienced some lingering auditory complications for an additional three- five minutes ( it sounded like a throbbing white noise). After that, I felt a little disoriented and tired. My aunt had taken me to Urgent Care, but they turned me away, saying I needed to go to the ER. However, by that time my symptoms had passed and I was feeling ok. So I went home and rested. By the next morning, I felt I had completely recovered

At 1259 client aged 19yo, was vaccinated in her left arm with the Janssen vaccine lot#205A21A. At 1306 client requested a bottle of water as she reported feeling dizzy. Vaccine monitor brought a bottle of water to vaccination room and immediately observed client's eyes begin to lose focus, so client was supported as she fainted, and placed safely on the floor with her legs elevated her legs on a chair and within seconds she regained consciousness. RN conducted a neuro-check on client and confirmed client was AxO x4. The zero gravity chair was retrieved and EMT summoned, and at 1310 client was assisted to her feet by Co-Lead RN and RN and transferred to this chair. At 1311 water was offered to client and she took a few sips and admitted she felt a lot better. At 1312 EMT took client's first set of vitals which were: BP 110/70, HR 60, RR18, and O2 98%. Co-lead confirmed with Vaccinator that client had been appropriately screened, that client had denied past syncopal episodes and had ate food today at 1000. At 1314, Co-Lead RN asked client again if she had ever experienced syncope, and she admitted that she had once when visiting her uncle in the hospital. Co-Lead then educated client that it is not uncommon to faint due to anxiety related to medical procedures and encouraged her to report this to her physician and to any medical personnel in the future during medical procedures so proper safety precautions can be engaged. Co-Lead then applied a cold pack to the back of client's neck, and EMT took a second set of vitals: BP 120/70, HR 63, O2 100%. Client remained in the vaccination room 1328 when she felt well enough to walk to the observation room escorted by EMT to complete a 30 minute observation period. At 1339 when EMT approached client to take her vitals again, client stated she was dizzy again, so EMT requested she remain for another 15 minutes and have a snack. At 1400, client stated she felt better, her vitals were taken for the last time by the EMT: BP 110/60, HR 56, O2 98%, and EMT then escorted client downstairs where her mother was waiting with the car. EMT and Co-Lead RN educated client to take it easy for the rest of the day and seek additional care with her PCP or Urgent Care if symptoms worsened. EMT observed client ambulating independently with a steady, even gait.

The patient received covid-19 vaccine ad26.cov2.s (suspension for injection, route of admin not reported, batch number: 1808609, and expiry: unknown) dose was not reported, 1 total administered on 20-MAR-2021 to right arm for prophylactic vaccination. Concomitant medications included omeprazole for abdominal pain. On 20-MAR-2021 two minutes after the vaccination, the patient had allergic reaction started with itching and redness on arms and upper chest. After ten minutes, the patient felt something wrong and consulted onsite EMT(emergency medical technician). Later the redness turned to hives with itchy to burning sensation. The EMT (emergency medical technician) was given intravenous Benadryl to the patient and hives got disappeared and redness remained. On the same day the patient went to the Emergency Room(ER) and stayed around seven hours. Pepcid and prednisone was given to the patient in ER (Emergency Room). The patient experienced chest tightness and warm and again Benadryl administered to the patient. The patient was also given Epipen while going home. On 21-MAR-2021, the patient experienced fatigue. On 22-MAR-2021, the patient had severe abdominal pain with 7-8 on pain scale, the abdominal pain was lasted for 24 hours and went away. The patient has been on Prilosec for the abdominal pain since a month. On 26- MAR-2021, the patient felt like hit by mack truck and fatigue. On 29-MAR-2021, the patient experienced light bruising legs far more easily than usual and had a bruise where she wore watch, but it was not deep bruising. On 05-APR-2021, the patient experienced black spot on vision in both eyes around 18:00-19:00 at night until went to bed, and lasted for 4 days. On 05-APR-2021, the patient experienced lightheaded and motion sickness when sitting or standing still; the patient also had neck pain. The patient's neck weakness was felt like the patient's head was going to fall off. The patient experienced neck weakness about once in a week around 15 minutes and also felt nauseous. On 09-APR-2021, the patient had severe migraine with light and sound sensitivity and had rapidly dilating pupils. The patient administered cocktail of medicine Benadryl, Toradol, and Compazine and this medicines helped the patient little bit with the pain. On 9-APR-2021, the patient experienced trouble reading for 2 days due to the dilatation of the both eyes. On an unspecified date, the patient experienced worse asthma than usual, and red spots on arms, leg, chest, chin, and neck. The spots were darker and shinier than usual. Other treatment medications (dates unspecified) included: Medrol for migraine. The patient had visited emergency room for allergic reaction. The action taken with covid-19 vaccine ad26.cov2.s was not applicable. The patient recovered from black spots in vision on 09-APR-2021, constricting pupils, and dilated pupils on 10-APR-2021, and severe abdominal pain on 23-MAR-2021, had not recovered from fatigue, light-headedness, nauseous, neck pain, severe migraine, light bruising on leg/arm, worse asthma, red spots on arms/leg/chest/chin/neck, and neck weakness, and the outcome of allergic reaction and felt like hit by a truck was not reported. 20 2021-05-25 gait disturbance I feel inclined to file this report in hopes that someone could study how receiving this vaccine aff... Read more
Close
I feel inclined to file this report in hopes that someone could study how receiving this vaccine affected my endometriosis. Please understand that I?m a proponent of vaccination and building herd immunity; however, women?s health is important and we have a right to be AWARE of ALL side effects. I?ve done my best to research this topic and was able to find very few sources on how COVID-19 vaccines impact menstruation. Aside from the lack of statistics, I found forums on social media platforms with women explaining how their menstrual cycles became irregular some way or another. I did experience the common side effects of fever, nausea, vomiting, diarrhea, soreness, and fatigue. In addition, I experienced severe cramps, back pain, thigh pain, groin pain, and nerve pain associated with the sciatic and obturator. I?m happy to be vaccinated because my immune system is far from the best, but if I were to have known that I would be unable to walk from the pain radiating from my back, pelvis, and thigh I would?ve opted for Moderna or Pfizer. At this point in time, I would NOT recommend the Janssen vaccine to someone with endometriosis. At that, this vaccine should be nowhere near as political as it is! My healthcare providers should be more willing to validate my symptoms, rather than saving face with the validity of the vaccine. I was told since my menstrual cycle is irregular I must coincidentally be getting my period, BUT I have not experienced any bleeding nor even spotting. I have no idea what the vaccine did to my body, I have no clue why it would induce such severe pain. I?m glad that the ?normal? symptoms have subsided by the second day, but the nerve pain complicates walking long distance or carrying heavy objects. I think I?ll eventually make a full recovery in the upcoming days, but this experience was so frightening. I laid on the floor for hours crying after I vomited up everything I had eaten. I couldn?t sleep because I couldn?t bear to lay down for long durations of time- and by that I mean more than ten minutes. It genuinely felt like I was getting my period, but whatever it was led to no external bleeding. Again, I?m grateful for the scientists who dedicate their lives to such integral work. I just wish I would?ve known about what was internally happening to my body beforehand, I would?ve chosen a different vaccine.

I had the typical soreness about 12 hours after the injection. No worries there. The next morning, on the 10th, around 11:40 AM, I started feeling extremely dizzy. The room started spinning. I was standing at the time, and I kept standing, but other than that, I had no control. My hearing starting going fuzzy, starting with ringing in my ears until it sounded like I was underwater. My vision started blurring, as well, eventually going completely black. For a solid 5-10 seconds, I could neither hear clearly nor see at all. I was conscious, because I could think relatively clearly, and I could feel my eyes blinking and could wiggle my fingers, but that was it. Once the episode passed, I immediately sat down. About a minute later, I started having excruciating abdominal pain. The pain was wracking my whole body, causing me to go pale (as I later saw once I could hobble to the bathroom) and making me sweat. After about twenty minutes, the whole thing passed and I was left with minor dizziness and slight nausea. Now, three days later, I still have some of the dizziness, but none of the blindness, deafness, or pain has returned. All other side effects, such as soreness, have completely left.

History of Present Illness This is a 22-year-old female who was previously healthy with no significant past medical history presenting to the emergency department after a syncopal event. She was getting her COVID-19 shot today (Johnson Johnson). After her shot she was texting on the phone with her mom, felt slightly dizzy and the next thing she remembers was lying on the ground. Witnesses reported that she syncopized and had some convulsive like behavior afterwards. She was not postictal or incontinent however. She reportedly hit the front of her forehead on the left side. She denies any chest pain, abdominal pain, hemoptysis, recent surgeries, immobilization or recent travel. She reports that when she woke up her hands felt a little bit tingly. When the fire department arrived they found her to be bradycardic however by the time the medics arrived her heart rate had resolved. Her blood sugar was 110 on the scene. Medics noted that she was orthostatic on the scene as well. She currently is feeling well, has no complaints. States that she has gotten dizzy before in the past with COVID vaccines.

It rapidly progressed within 3 hours to the point where my entire left side was numb and I had foot droop, slurred speech and a severe migraine, often associated with a stroke. I was immediately taken to the ER where a CT of my brain, labs, and EKGs were performed due to symptoms I was experiencing closely related to neurological issues. It came down to a diagnosis of a hemiplegic migraine, which is a rare and serious form of a migraine with symptoms mimicking a stroke. I was discharged 3 days later and was told to follow up with my primary care doctor and neurologist for further long term care....4 days later and I?m finally able to walk but definitely no where?s near my normal self. Within seconds of receiving the vaccine I began to feel slightly dizzy. By the time I walked across the room to the observation table I was feeling lightheaded. They sat me down, gave me water and a cookie, but about 2min after the injection the dizziness was so intense that I began to black out. I was unconscious for about 1-2min, then came to but my vision was still unclear. I was taken via wheelchair to the paramedics on the opposite end of the gymnasium, and at this point I was heavily perspiring and very pale but still coherent. I felt my vision and dizziness significantly improve after being able to lay down. I was transported to the hospital for observation but had much improved by the time I arrived. An EKG, bloodwork, and cardiac tests were recommended to discern possible underlying heart related conditions, but I declined because I already had a PAT for thyroid surgery scheduled the next day that would be running those same tests. This reaction was likely due to not having eaten for several hours prior to the vaccine. After about an hour I felt well enough to drive myself back home and dealt with mild aches and pains that evening, chills, and a low grade fever all of which resolved themselves by the next morning.

The next day (5/2) my emotional state returned almost to normal, but I was still "stupid", and the leg cramps continued. I spent most of the day sleeping. I also drank obscene amounts of tea that I didn't urinate out, so I would assume that if I wasn't chugging tea like a frat boy on a keg during spring break, I would have suffered dehydration. On 5/3 my mental state returned basically to normal. The leg cramps continued. Presumptive dehydration period ended. On 5/4 the leg cramps began to subside, and my period became more normal (bloodlike, watery). On 5/5 the leg cramps and period ended.

Around 6:30pm I became very hot and dizzy, I sat down and splashed cold water on my face which seemed to help a little. I took tylenol (acetaminophen 500mg) and two glasses of water. As the night progressed, my lower back started to hurt and my headache continued to progress. I went to bed early to sleep it off but was woken up by overheating and headache. I took more tylenol around 3am and grabbed an icepack, this seemed to help alleviate the symptoms.

After vomiting, main discomfort came from cramps. Patient did not report feeling faint, or lightheaded.
